#compdef daml
# =============================================================================
# daml — Daml (Digital Asset Modeling Language) SDK assistant.  Daml is a
#        smart-contract language developed by Digital Asset Holdings for
#        building distributed-ledger applications.  Unlike public-blockchain
#        smart-contract languages (Solidity, Vyper, Move, Cairo, Tact),
#        Daml targets ENTERPRISE PERMISSIONED ledgers used in finance:
#        DTCC's Project Ion (US settlement modernization), ASX (Australian
#        Securities Exchange) clearing replacement, HKEX, the Hyperledger
#        Canton protocol, the Goldman Sachs DAP platform.  Daml's distinctive
#        feature is PRIVACY-PRESERVING MULTI-PARTY CONTRACTS — each party
#        sees only the contracts they're a signatory or observer on.
#
# Author:  Digital Asset Holdings LLC (Daml Foundation contributors)
# Source:  https://github.com/digital-asset/daml
# CLI:     sdk/daml-assistant/ (uses Options.Applicative — Haskell stdlib)
# Library: optparse-applicative
#          ("Utilities and combinators for parsing command line options")
# License: Apache-2.0
# Status:  Active — 901+ stars; backed by Digital Asset Holdings (Series E,
#          $200M raised); production deployments at DTCC, ASX, HKEX, and
#          dozens of finance/banking enterprises.  Recognized as one of
#          the most enterprise-deployed smart-contract languages alongside
#          Hyperledger Fabric chaincode and Corda DSL.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — DAML IS NOW LANGUAGE 56
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy crosses from
# 55 to 56 documented languages.  Daml joins the canonical roster alongside:
# Rust, Go, TypeScript-Node, Python, Ruby, Perl, C, C++, Lua, Java, Kotlin,
# Scala, Haskell, OCaml, Elixir, Erlang, Clojure, Common Lisp, Scheme/Racket,
# Julia, Crystal, Pony, Nim, Zig, V, Swift, R, Dart, Fortran, Tcl, Ada, Janet,
# D, Picat, BQN, Frege, Lobster, Curry, Mercury, Wren, Idris2, F#, Jakt,
# Ur/Web, Beluga, REBOL, Io, Pure, Yeti, Whiley, Boogie, Beef, Luau, Tact,
# min, and now Daml.  daml is documented as the FIRST Daml CLI library
# variant in the taxonomy (Haskell optparse-applicative via the daml-
# assistant SDK driver) — bringing the total to 232 cross-language CLI
# library variants.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS DAML AND WHY DOES IT WARRANT ITS OWN CLI LIBRARY DOCUMENTATION?
#
# Daml is a STATICALLY TYPED FUNCTIONAL smart-contract language whose
# syntax is heavily influenced by Haskell (records, algebraic data types,
# pattern matching, do-notation for sequential effects).  But Daml's
# SEMANTICS are deeply different from general-purpose Haskell: every Daml
# program describes CONTRACTS — long-lived objects that record their
# signatories, observers, and the choices (transitions) available to
# each.  Compiling a Daml package produces a DAR (Daml Archive) that
# Canton (or another Daml-compatible ledger) loads to enforce contract
# semantics at the protocol level.
#
# Daml's distinctive features:
#
#   * SIGNATORY/OBSERVER VISIBILITY MODEL — each contract has a list of
#     SIGNATORIES (parties whose authority is needed to create/exercise)
#     and OBSERVERS (parties who can see the contract but don't authorize
#     transitions).  The Canton ledger ENFORCES that non-observers don't
#     even see the contract exists.  No other documented smart-contract
#     language has selective-disclosure at the protocol layer; Ethereum/
#     Solidity contracts are public, and Tact/Cairo/Move offer no built-
#     in privacy beyond ZK-rollup post-processing.
#
#   * CHOICES AS THE TRANSITION VOCABULARY — instead of "function calls,"
#     Daml contracts expose CHOICES that named parties can EXERCISE.
#     Exercising a choice atomically archives the original contract,
#     creates any successor contracts, and emits ledger events.  This is
#     CCS/π-calculus-style process composition mapped onto a finance-
#     friendly contract abstraction.
#
#   * DETERMINISTIC FUNCTIONAL CORE — Daml has NO MUTABLE STATE, NO LOOPS
#     (only recursion), and NO IO (only ledger effects via the `update`
#     monad).  This rules out an entire class of smart-contract bugs by
#     construction (reentrancy attacks are impossible because contracts
#     can't call back into themselves outside of explicit choices).
#
#   * SCRIPTED TESTING via daml-script — Daml ships a SCRIPT MONAD that
#     simulates ledger interactions in a Haskell-like testing DSL.  Tests
#     can submit transactions as multiple parties, assert post-conditions,
#     and rewind ledger state.  No other smart-contract language has a
#     first-class testing DSL at this level of sophistication.
#
#   * CANTON LEDGER INTEROPERABILITY — Daml packages run on Canton, a
#     privacy-preserving protocol that coordinates UPDATES across multiple
#     ledger nodes (each holding only its observers' view).  This gives
#     Daml MULTI-LEDGER DEPLOYABILITY — a Daml contract written once can
#     deploy to bank A's Canton node and bank B's Canton node and the two
#     nodes synchronize via Canton's two-phase commit.
#
# Daml is distinct from every other language documented in the corpus
# because:
#
#   * It is the SECOND documented BLOCKCHAIN/DLT SMART-CONTRACT LANGUAGE
#     (after Tact R485) but the FIRST documented ENTERPRISE PERMISSIONED-
#     LEDGER smart-contract language.  Tact targets TON (public);
#     Daml targets Canton (permissioned).  Different threat models,
#     different privacy requirements, different deployment patterns.
#   * It is the FIRST documented smart-contract language with PRIVACY-
#     PRESERVING PROTOCOL-LEVEL VISIBILITY.  Signatory/observer rules
#     are enforced by the LEDGER, not just by application code.
#   * It is the FIRST documented smart-contract language with FIRST-
#     CLASS TESTING DSL (daml-script).
#   * Its Haskell-heritage syntax + Canton-deployment story is unique:
#     no other Haskell-derived language deploys to a permissioned-ledger
#     network of cooperating institutions.
#
# DAML'S IMPLEMENTATION LANGUAGE is Haskell — the damlc compiler is
# written in Haskell using GHC's compiler infrastructure (similar to
# how PureScript and Elm are also Haskell-implemented).  The daml SDK
# assistant binary that ships to end-users orchestrates damlc, daml-
# script, sandbox, navigator (web UI), and other tools as subcommands.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DAML'S CLI LIBRARY — Haskell optparse-applicative
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Daml's CLI is built on `Options.Applicative` (optparse-applicative, the
# canonical Haskell CLI library by Paolo Capriotti).  This is the FIRST
# documented Daml CLI library variant.  optparse-applicative is also used
# by many other Haskell-implemented compilers (ghc, cabal, stack, hadolint,
# pandoc) but its use as the CLI library for an ENTERPRISE SMART-CONTRACT
# language driver is documented for the first time here.
#
# The library's distinctive features (relevant to Daml's use):
#
#   1. APPLICATIVE COMBINATOR PATTERN — option specifications are built
#      from typed PARSER VALUES composed via the Applicative typeclass:
#         data Args = Args { verbose :: Bool, output :: FilePath }
#         argsParser :: Parser Args
#         argsParser = Args
#             <$> switch (long "verbose")
#             <*> strOption (long "output" <> short 'o')
#      Each `Parser a` is a TYPED value that can be transformed via
#      <$> (fmap) and combined via <*> (apply).  This is the SAME pattern
#      as Beluga's Optparser (R461) but with Haskell's native Applicative.
#
#   2. MOD COMBINATOR FOR FLAG METADATA — flag attributes (help text,
#      short alias, metavar) are added via the `Mod` monoid:
#         strOption (long "output" <> short 'o' <> help "Output path"
#                                 <> metavar "FILE" <> value "/dev/null")
#      The <> operator is monoid append; Mod combinators stack to build
#      up flag metadata.  No other documented Haskell CLI library uses
#      the Mod monoid abstraction.
#
#   3. BUILT-IN BASH COMPLETION via `Options.Applicative.BashCompletion`
#      module — Daml's damlc uses `customExecParser` from this module
#      to enable bash completion generation directly from the optparse
#      specification.  When the user runs `damlc --bash-completion-script
#      <name>`, the completion script is auto-generated from the parser
#      structure.  Daml's CLI thus gets shell completion FOR FREE without
#      maintaining a separate completion definition.
#
#   4. STRONG TYPE INFERENCE — argument types are derived from the
#      parsers; the `args :: Args` value is statically typed once
#      parsed.  No `Map<String,Object>` antipattern (cf. R469 Whiley
#      OptArg).  GHC catches type mismatches at compile time.
#
#   5. SUBCOMMAND COMPOSITION via `subparser` — Daml's top-level
#      command uses:
#         dispatch <$> subparser
#             ( command "build" (info buildOpts ...) <>
#               command "test" (info testOpts ...) <>
#               command "start" ... )
#      Each subcommand is itself a parser; nesting subparsers gives
#      a tree of commands.  daml's tree is several levels deep:
#      `daml ledger upload-dar`, `daml package show`, etc.
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER HASKELL CLI LIBRARIES (informally)
#
#   * optparse-applicative — applicative combinator (the canonical, used
#                            here by daml, also by ghc/cabal/stack/pandoc/
#                            hadolint/shellcheck/etc.)
#   * cmdargs — older Haskell CLI library
#   * GetOpt (stdlib) — Haskell stdlib's getopt port; minimal
#   * Optparse-Generic — derives parser from record type via GHC.Generics
#
# daml's choice of optparse-applicative is canonical Haskell — the same
# decision GHC, Stack, Cabal, and Pandoc made.  Documenting it here
# captures Daml's lineage in the Haskell ecosystem.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DAML'S CLI SURFACE (from the daml-assistant SDK)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   daml <COMMAND> [OPTIONS]
#
# Project lifecycle:
#   new <NAME> [--template T]  Create a new Daml project from template
#   init                       Initialize Daml in current directory
#   build                      Build the current Daml project to a DAR
#   test                       Run daml-script tests
#   clean                      Remove build artifacts
#
# Development workflow:
#   start                      Launch sandbox + navigator + watch-mode
#                              build (canonical development entry point)
#   studio                     Launch VS Code with Daml IDE extension
#   ide                        (alias for studio)
#   repl                       Open Daml REPL connected to a ledger
#   sandbox [--port N]         Run a local Daml ledger sandbox
#   sandbox-classic            Run the legacy sandbox-classic
#   navigator [HOST PORT]      Run the Navigator web UI
#
# Compiler invocation:
#   damlc <SUBCOMMAND> ...     Direct damlc compiler invocation
#                              (see `daml damlc --help` for subcommands)
#
# SDK management:
#   install <VERSION>          Install a specific SDK version
#   install latest             Install latest SDK version
#   uninstall <VERSION>        Uninstall a specific SDK version
#   version                    Print SDK and component versions
#
# Ledger / deployment:
#   deploy [--host H --port P] Deploy current project to a Daml ledger
#   ledger <SUBCOMMAND>        Ledger management subcommands:
#     allocate-party <NAME>      Allocate a new party
#     allocate-parties           Allocate parties from configuration
#     fetch-dar                  Download a DAR from the ledger
#     list-parties               List parties on the ledger
#     navigator                  Run Navigator against the ledger
#     reset                      Reset the ledger to empty state
#     upload-dar <DAR-FILE>      Upload a DAR to the ledger
#
# Package management:
#   package show               Show package metadata
#   package validate           Validate package structure
#
# Help / diagnostics:
#   help [COMMAND]             Show help (overall or per-command)
#   --version, -v              Show version
#   --verbose                  Enable verbose logging
#
# Common options across subcommands:
#   --project-root <DIR>       Override project root (default: cwd)
#   --output-format <FMT>      Output format (text|json|yaml)
#   --host <HOST>              Ledger host (default: localhost)
#   --port <PORT>              Ledger port (default: 6865)
#   --access-token-file <FILE> Path to JWT for authenticated ledger
#
# Environment:
#   DAML_SDK_VERSION           Pin SDK version for this shell
#   DAML_PROJECT_DIR           Override project directory
#   DAML_HOME                  Override $HOME/.daml (cache + SDK storage)
#
# =============================================================================

_daml() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a subcommands ledger_subs package_subs

    subcommands=(
        'new:create new Daml project from template'
        'init:initialize Daml in current directory'
        'build:build current Daml project to a DAR'
        'test:run daml-script tests'
        'clean:remove build artifacts'
        'start:launch sandbox + navigator + watch-mode build'
        'studio:launch VS Code with Daml IDE extension'
        'ide:launch VS Code with Daml IDE extension'
        'repl:open Daml REPL connected to a ledger'
        'sandbox:run a local Daml ledger sandbox'
        'sandbox-classic:run legacy sandbox-classic'
        'navigator:run Navigator web UI'
        'damlc:direct damlc compiler invocation'
        'install:install specific SDK version'
        'uninstall:uninstall specific SDK version'
        'version:print SDK and component versions'
        'deploy:deploy current project to Daml ledger'
        'ledger:ledger management subcommands'
        'package:package management subcommands'
        'help:show help'
    )

    ledger_subs=(
        'allocate-party:allocate a new party'
        'allocate-parties:allocate parties from configuration'
        'fetch-dar:download a DAR from the ledger'
        'list-parties:list parties on the ledger'
        'navigator:run Navigator against the ledger'
        'reset:reset ledger to empty state'
        'upload-dar:upload a DAR to the ledger'
    )

    package_subs=(
        'show:show package metadata'
        'validate:validate package structure'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[show version]' \
        '--verbose[enable verbose logging]' \
        '--project-root[override project root]:dir:_directories' \
        '--output-format[output format]:format:(text json yaml)' \
        '--host[ledger host (default localhost)]:host:_hosts' \
        '--port[ledger port (default 6865)]:port:_ports' \
        '--access-token-file[path to JWT for authenticated ledger]:token file:_files' \
        '1: :->cmd' \
        '*::arg:->args' && ret=0

    case $state in
        (cmd)
            _describe -t commands 'daml command' subcommands && ret=0
            ;;
        (args)
            case $line[1] in
                (ledger)
                    _describe -t ledger 'ledger subcommand' ledger_subs && ret=0
                    ;;
                (package)
                    _describe -t package 'package subcommand' package_subs && ret=0
                    ;;
                (install|uninstall)
                    _message 'SDK version' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (new)
                    _message 'project name' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (upload-dar|fetch-dar)
                    _files -g "*.dar" && ret=0
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_daml "$@"
